ce:section.ce:para:
The description of MIT is usually a method of constructing artificial materials with antibody patterns that contain customized recognition sites. However, MIT has become a recognized molecular recognition analysis tool. Molecularly imprinted polymers (MIPs) obtained through this technology have many advantages, such as their economical and simple preparation methods, excellent physical and chemical stability, and excellent selectivity. (Kazemifard, Ensafi, & Rezaei, 2020; Pan, Chen, Ma, & Pan, 2018; Van Royen, Dubruel, Van Weyenberg, & Daeseleire, 2016; Zhang, Tang, & Liu, 2019). Therefore, MIPs can be used as identification elements in sensors to provide a good basis for the research of various sensors. In fact, MIPs can be designed for any target of interest. At present, most reports combine MIPs with single-emission CDs which as the signal source to form highly selective fluorescent imprinted composite materials for detecting a variety of substances (Table 2
                        ). For example, Bhogal and others reported an environmentally friendly core-shell material based on CDs cores and MIPs shells, which achieved the highly selective fluorescence detection of ketoprofen (Bhogal, Kaur, Maheshwari, & Malik, 2019). Magnetic nanoparticles such as Fe3O4 nanoparticles, as a functional material with high enrichment ability and excellent water dispersibility (Liu et al., 2009), can be used in combination with MIT, a CDs-based single-emission magnetic nanoimprint polymer with high adsorption performance can be prepared to achieve rapid detection. Recently, Lv et al. used one-pot method to synthesize a new type of single-emitting magnetic CDs (M-CDs) with the assistance of Fe3O4 nanoparticles, the prepared M-CDs@MIPs showed high selectivity and sensitive photosensitivity to bovine haemoglobin (BHb). Under optimal conditions, the fluorescence intensity decreased linearly with the BHb concentration in the range of 0.05–16.0 μM, and the LOD is 17.3 nM (Lv, Xie, & Zhang, 2018). Similarly, Wang et al. chose single-emitting CDs as fluorescent sensor elements, obtained magnetic covalent organic framework (MCOF) as adsorbents and structural support materials by grafting Fe3O4 nanoparticles, synthesized MCOFs@MIPs@CDs in an inverse microemulsion system (Fig. 7
                        A), the composite material has a very short detection time (less than 1 min) and good sensitivity for 2,4,6-trinitrophenol (TNP) in water samples, the LOD is 0.1 nM (Wang et al., 2020). Traditional MIPs are highly cross-linked and have a rigid structure, while the natural target molecule has a more flexible and changeable conformation, which limits the interaction between the polymer and target molecule. In recent years, doping polymers have been widely reported. A study introduced highly luminescent blue CDs and embedded them in a MOF with a high specific surface area and high porosity. Through the surface molecular imprinting process, CDs@MOFs@MIPs was obtained for the detection of trace quercetin (QCT). Due to the introduction of the porous MOF, CDs@MOFs@MIPs showed a faster reaction rate than that of CDs-embedded MIPs. As the QCT concentration increased from 0 to 50.0 μM, the fluorescence intensity of CDs@MOFs@MIPs showed a good linear decrease with an LOD of 2.9 nM (L. H. Xu, Pan, et al., 2019). In addition, to improve the detection sensitivity of analytes, a study developed a one-to-one fit design, which introduced restricted access materials (RAM) to synthesize CDs@RAM-MIPs for detecting metronidazole (MNZ). The obtained CDs@RAM-MIPs used CDs as the fluorescent material, MNZ as the template molecule, and glycidyl methacrylate (GMA) as the comonomer in the molecular imprinting system. Since GMA contains an epoxy ring, it can effectively decrease interference polymerization after the reaction. The epoxy ring was opened with diluted perchloric acid, which provided a hydrophilic modification to the surface of CDs@RAM-MIPs and prevented the adhesion of macromolecules. Thus, the selective recognition ability was improved. As the concentration of MNZ increased, the fluorescence of the CD was quenched. A possible mechanism of fluorescence quenching was proposed as photoelectron transfer (PET). Under the excitation of photons, the electrons of the CD underwent a transition from the ground state to excited state, and then, the excited electrons returned to the valence band and fluorescence appeared. After adding MNZ, the excited electrons of the CD directly jumped to the unoccupied molecular orbital of the lowest energy state in the complex, causing electron transfer and fluorescence quenching (Fig. 7B) (Liu, Ding, Zhang, & Ding, 2019).
